        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Rayon paper"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "PAPER_RAYON",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-PLANT_LEAVES",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Plant leaves, such as banana leaves, including wet or dry leaves. In some cases, leaves are pre-softened by steaming."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Plant leaves"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "PLANT_LEAVES",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-PLASTIC_BIO_PLASTIC",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Plastic materials made from biomass, but may have exactly the same properties as ordinary plastic. Sometimes these plastics are biodegradable."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Bioplastic"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "PLASTIC_BIO_PLASTIC",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-PLASTIC_OTHER",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A non-specific material made of any of numerous organic synthetic or processed materials that are mostly thermoplastic or thermosetting polymers of high molecular weight and that can be made into objects, films, or filaments."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Plastic other"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "PLASTIC_OTHER",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-PLASTIC_THERMOPLASTICS",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A non-specific substance that becomes soft and pliable when heated, without a change in its intrinsic properties. Polystyrene and polyethylene are thermoplastics."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Thermoplastics"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "PLASTIC_THERMOPLASTICS",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_APET",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene Terephthalate, amorphous (APET) has a very high transparency, is flame retardant and suitable for direct food contact."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene terephthalate, amorphous (APET)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_APET",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_BOPP",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Biaxially oriented PP (BOPP) films are characterized by their tear, impact and puncture resistance. The film is mainly used in food packaging, e.g. as candy wrap or wrapping for chocolate bars."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polypropylene, longitudinally and laterally stretched (BOPP)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_BOPP",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_CELLULOSE_ACETATE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Cellulose acetate is one of the most important esters of cellulose. Depending on the way it has been processed cellulose acetate can be used for a wide variety of applications, e.g. films, membranes or fibres."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Acetate"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_CELLULOSE_ACETATE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_CPET",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Crystallized polyethylene terephthalate (CPET) is a variation of standard PET which has been crystallized for heat resistance, rigidity, and toughness."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Crystallized polyethylene terephthalate (CPET)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_CPET",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_EPOXY",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Epoxy resins are thermoset polymers which are frequently used as coatings for metal packaging such as soft-drink cans."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Epoxy"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_EPOXY",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_EPS",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Expanded polystyrene is a rigid, tough, closed cell and lightweight thermoplastic foam material. It is manufactured by expanding spherical beads in a mold, using heat and pressure to fuse the beads together. While each individual bead is a closed cell environment, there are significant open spaces between each bead."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Expanded polystyrene (EPS)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_EPS",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_EVA",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Ethylene vinyl acetate, a copolymer of 60 to 90% ethylene and 40 to 10% vinyl acetate. Packaging applications include soft films, coatings, hot melt adhesives, wine cork substitutes, and closure seals for plastic and metal container caps."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Ethylene vinyl acetate (EVA)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_EVA",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_EVOH",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Ethylene vinyl alcohol, a copolymer of ethylene and vinyl alcohol. A plastic resin commonly used in food applications to provide barrier to oxygen and other gases."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Ethylene vinyl alcohol (EVOH)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_EVOH",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_HDPE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "High-Density PolyEthylene (HDPE) is a polyethylene thermoplastic made from petroleum. A strong, relatively opaque form of polyethylene having a dense structure with few side branches off the main carbon backbone. Can be applied to bottles, flasks and caps."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "High density polyethylene (HDPE)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_HDPE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_LDPE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Low-density polyethylene (LDPE) is a polyethylene thermoplastic made from petroleum. A strong form of polyethylene having a less dense structure with more side branches off the main carbon backbone (on about 2% of the carbon atoms) than HDPE; therefore its tensile strength is lower, and its resilience is higherMade in translucent or opaque variations, it is quite flexible, and tough to the degree of being almost unbreakable. It is widely used for manufacturing various containers, dispensing bottles, wash bottles, tubing, plastic bags for computer components, and various moulded laboratory equipment. Its most common use is in plastic bags."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Low-density polyethylene (LDPE)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_LDPE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_LLDPE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Linear low density polyethylene is a linear polyethylene with a significant number of short branches on the polymer backbone. It is commonly made by copolymerization of ethylene with longer-chain olefins. It is different from LDPE due to the absence of long chain branches which gives it higher tensile strength, impact and puncture resistance than LDPE. Common uses of LLDPE are plastic bags, wraps, stretch wraps, pouches, covers and lids."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Linear low density polyethylene"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_LLDPE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_MDPE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Medium-density polyethylene is a type of polyethylene defined by a density range of 0.926-0.940 g/cm3. MDPE is typically used in shrink films, sacks, packaging film and carrier bags."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Medium-density polyethylene"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_MDPE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_NYLON",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Packaging applications include oven-baking bags (nylon 6 and nylon 66) and barrier layers (MXD6 and nylon 6) for PET and HDPE bottles. Very occasionally, bottles can be made of nylon."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Nylon"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_NYLON",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_OPP",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Oriented polypropylene (OPP) is made of a soft polypropylene material which is stretched in a transverse or longitudinal direction (monoaxial) and becomes therefore brittle. Also known as: biaxially oriented polypropylene (BOPP), CAS Registry Number: 9003-07-0"
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Oriented polypropylene (OPP)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_OPP",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_OTHER",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The value needed is not listed or is not defined within this list's individual code value and definitions of polymer. Please send a work request into GS1 or your solution provider requesting the code you are searching for."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polymers Other"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_OTHER",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PA",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A polymer with repeating units linked by amide bonds. Polyamides (PA) occur both naturally and artificially, examples of naturally occurring polyamides are proteins, such as wool and silk. Artificially made polyamides can be nylons, aramids, and sodium poly(aspartate)."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyamide (PA)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PA",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PAN",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyacrylonitril is a organic polymer which is frequently used in fibres for textiles. As fibres the material is frequently referred to as acrylic."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyacrylonitril (PAN)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PAN",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PB",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre formed of linear macromolecules having in the chain the recurring ureylene (NH-CO-NH) functional group."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polycarbamide (PB)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PB",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PC",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polycarbonate, a transparent thermoplastic which is used in a wide variety of applications including CDs and DVDs, eyeglasses, cell phone covers, laptops as well as packaging applications such as bottles."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polycarbonate (PC)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PC",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PCL",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polycaprolactone is a biodegradable polyester which is also used in in the manufacturing of polyurethanes. It is also used in blends with thermoplastic starch to improve properties and can also be used as a plasticizer to PVC."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polycaprolactone (PCL)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PCL",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A thermoplastic composed of the polymers of ethylene."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene (PE)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PEN",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene naphthalate is a polymer with good barrier properties (unlike Polyethylene terephthalate). It is well-suited for production of the amber-coloured bottles meant for packing beverages like beer."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene naphthalate (PEN)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PEN",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_POLYESTER",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre formed of linear macromolecules comprising at least 85% (by mass) in the chain of an ester of a diol and terephthalic acid."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyester (PES)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_POLYESTER",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PET",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene terephthalate is a thermoplastic polymer resin of the polyester family and is used in synthetic fibres. Can be applied to bottles, flasks and caps."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene terephthalate (PET)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PET",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PETG",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene Terephthalate Glycol (PETG) is a PET modified with glycol, which is characterized by its aqueous properties (viscosity). Applications are found in injection molding."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyethylene terephthalate glycol (PETG)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PETG",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PHA",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyhydroxyalkanoates are linear polyesters produced in nature by bacterial fermentation of sugar or lipids."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyhydroxyalkanoates (PHA)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PHA",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PI",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre formed from synthetic linear macromolecules having in the chain recurring imide units."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyimide (PI)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PI",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PLA",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polylactic acid or Polylactide is a biodegradable, thermoplastic, aliphatic polyester derived from lactic acid."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polylactic acid or Polylactide (PLA)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PLA",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PMMA",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polymethyl Methacrylate (PMMA) is often used as a lightweight and shatterproof alternative to glass, due to its transparency, brilliance and scratch resistance, PMMA is therefore often referred to as acrylic glass."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polymethyl methacrylate (PMMA)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PMMA",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_POM",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyoxymethylene (POM) is a thermoplastic with good mechanical properties and high dimensional stability. Fields of application are the automotive industry and electrical engineering, in packaging it is used for e.g. spray cans, gas lighter tanks, gas ampoules. Also known as acetal, polyacetal, and polyformaldehyde."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyoxymethylene (POM)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_POM",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PP",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A non-specific material made of various thermoplastic plastics or fibres that are polymers of propylene."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polypropylene (PP)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PP",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PS",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A polymer prepared by the polymerization of styrene as the sole monomer."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polystyrene (PS)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PS",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PU",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyurethanes are primarily thermoset resins which are used in the manufacture of flexible and rigid foams, microcellular foam seals and gaskets, as well as high performance adhesives, surface coatings and sealants. Polyurethane can also be used to make synthetic fibres."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyurethane (PU)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PU",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PVA",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyvinyl alcohol (PVA or PVOH) is a biodegradable and highly water soluble polymer with high gas and grease barrier. Common uses for PVA are paper adhesives, paper coatings, as a self-standing water soluble films as well as blends to improve processability of thermoplastic starch."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyvinyl alcohol (PVA)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PVA",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PVC",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A polymer of vinyl chloride used especially for electrical insulation, films, and pipes."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyvinyl chloride (PVC)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PVC",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_PVDC",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyvinylidene chloride is primarily used as a barrier coating to provide barrier against fat, vapour and gases."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Polyvinylidene chloride (PVDC)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_PVDC",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_SAN",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Styrene acrylonitrile (SAN) is a copolymer transparent and rigid plastic. Examples of applications are kitchenware and cosmetic packaging."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Styrene acrylonitrile (SAN)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_SAN",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_TPS",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Thermoplastic starch is obtained through destructurization of natural starch through exposure to shear and heat. TPS is most frequently used in blends with biodegradable synthetic polymers such as PCL and PVA."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Thermoplastic starch (TPS)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_TPS",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-POLYMER_XPS",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Extruded polystyrene is a rigid, tough, closed cell and lightweight thermoplastic foam material. It is manufactured using a process of extrusion that produces a homogeneous 'closed cell' matrix with each cell fully enclosed by polystyrene walls."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Extruded polystyrene (XPS)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "POLYMER_XPS",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_PROTEIN",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre obtained from natural protein substances regenerated and stabilised through the action of chemical agents."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Protein"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_PROTEIN",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_RAMIE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre obtained from the bast of Boehmeria nivea and Boehmeria tenacissima."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Ramie"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_RAMIE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-RUBBER",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A strong elastic synthetic substance made either by improving the qualities of natural rubber or by an industrial process using petroleum and coal products."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Rubber"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "RUBBER",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_SILK",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre obtained exclusively from silk-secreting insects."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Silk"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_SILK",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_SISAL",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre obtained from the leaves of Agave sisalana."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Sisal"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_SISAL",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_SUNN",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre from the bast of Crotalaria juncea."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Sunn hemp"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_SUNN",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_TRIACETATE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Cellulose acetate fibre wherein at least 92% of the hydroxyl groups are acetylated."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Triacetate"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_TRIACETATE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_TRIVINYL",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre formed of acrylonitrile terpolymer, a chlorinated vinyl monomer and a third vinyl monomer, none of which represents as much as 50% of the total mass."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Trivinyl"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_TRIVINYL",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_TRUE_HEMP",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre obtained from the bast of hemp (Cannabis sativa)."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "True hemp"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_TRUE_HEMP",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-VINYL",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A non-specific polymer of a vinyl compound or a product (as a resin or a textile fibre) made from such a polymer."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Vinyl"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "VINYL",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_VINYLAL",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre formed of linear macromolecules whose chain is constituted by poly(vinyl alcohol) with differing levels of acetalisation."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Vinylal"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_VINYLAL",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_VISCOSE",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Regenerated cellulose fibre obtained by the viscose process for filament and discontinuous fibre."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Viscose"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_VISCOSE",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_HARDBOARD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Hardboard (not to be confused with hardwood), also called High-Density Fiberboard (HDF), is a type of fibreboard, which is similar to particle board and medium-density fiberboard, but is denser, much stronger and harder because it is made out of exploded wood fibres which have been highly compressed. Consequently, the density of hardboard is 31 lbs or more per cubic foot (500 kg/m³ and is usually about 50-65 lbs per cubic foot (800-1040 kg/m³). It differs from particle board in that the bonding of the wood fibers requires no additional materials, although resin is often added. Unlike particle board, it will not split or crack."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Hardboard"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_HARDBOARD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_HARDWOOD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A general term referring to any variety of broad-leaved, deciduous trees, and the wood from those trees. The term has nothing to do with the actual hardness of the wood; some hardwoods are softer than certain softwood (evergreen) species."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Hardwood"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_HARDWOOD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_MEDIUM_DENSITY_FIBREBOARD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Medium-Density Fibreboard (MDF) is an engineered wood product made by breaking down hardwood or softwood residuals into wood fibres, combining them with wax and a resin binder, and forming panels by applying high temperature and pressure. MDF is generally denser than plywood. It is made up of separated fibres, but can be used as a building material similar in application to plywood. It is stronger and much more dense than particle board."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Medium density fibreboard"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_MEDIUM_DENSITY_FIBREBOARD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_ORIENTED_STRANDBOARD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Oriented Strand Board (OSB), also known as sterling board, sterling OSB, aspenite, and smartply, is an engineered wood particle board formed by adding adhesives and then compressing layers of wood strands (flakes) in specific orientations. OSB may have a rough and variegated surface with the individual strips of around 2.5 x 15 cm (1\\\" x 6\\\"), lying unevenly across each other and comes in a variety of types."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Oriented strand board (OSB)"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_ORIENTED_STRANDBOARD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_OTHER",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The value needed is not listed or is not defined within this list's individual code value and definitions of wood. Please send a work request into GS1 or your solution provider requesting the code you are searching for."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Wood other"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_OTHER",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_PARTICLE_BOARD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Particle Board, also known as particleboard, chipboard, and Low-Density Fibreboard (LDF), is an engineered wood product manufactured from wood chips, sawmill shavings, or sawdust, and a synthetic resin or other suitable binder, which is pressed and extruded. Particle board is a composite material."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Particle board"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_PARTICLE_BOARD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_PLYWOOD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Plywood, a manufactured wood panel similar to LDF, MDF, and HDF, is made from layering thin sheets of wood. Plywood layers (called veneers or plies) are glued together, with adjacent plies having their wood grain rotated relative to adjacent layers up to 90 degrees. All plywoods bind resin and wood fibre sheets (cellulose cells are long, strong and thin) to form a composite material."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Plywood"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_PLYWOOD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-WOOD_SOFTWOOD",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "General term used to describe lumber produced from needle and/or cone bearing trees (Conifers)."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Softwood"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "WOOD_SOFTWOOD",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_WOOL",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre from sheep's or lambs' fleeces (Ovis aries) or a mixture of fibres from sheep's or lambs' fleeces and the hair of the following animals: alpaca, llama, camel, kashmir goat, angora goat, angora rabbit, vicuna, yak, guanaco, cashgora goat, beaver, otter."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Wool"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_WOOL",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-FIBRE_ELASTOLEFIN",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Fibre composed of at least 95% (by mass) of macromolecules partially cross-linked, made up from ethylene and at least one other olefin and which, when stretched to one and a half times its original length and released, recovers rapidly and substantially to its initial length."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Elastolefin"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "FIBRE_ELASTOLEFIN",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:MaterialCode-MINERAL_QUARTZ",
      "@type": "gs1de:MaterialCode",
      "rdfs:comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A hard white or colourless mineral consisting of silicon dioxide, found widely in igneous, metamorphic, and sedimentary rocks."
      },
      "rdfs:label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Quartz"
      },
      "skos:prefLabel": "MINERAL_QUARTZ",
      "sw:term_status": "testing"
    },
    {
      "@id": "gs1de:PackagingRecyclabilityAssessmentSpecificationCode",
